  "hash": "sha256:a3f1c2e4b7d09e6f5c8a2b1d4e7f0c3a9b6d2e5f8c1a4b7d0e3f6c9a2b5d8e1f4",
  "signature": "ed25519:9c4e2a7f1b3d6e8c0f5a2d4b7e1c3f6a9d2b5e8c1f4a7d0b3e6c9f2a5d8b1e4c7",
  "hasCredibilityFactor": [
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Software quality assurance",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Commercial FEA solver (Ansys Mechanical) with documented verification test suite; version-controlled analysis files; audit trail of solver settings.",
      "rationale": "Ansys Mechanical 2021 R2 was used throughout. The solver carries ISO 9001-certified QMS documentation and a published verification and validation test matrix covering linear and nonlinear structural elements. Analysis input files were stored in a Git repository with commit hashes recorded at each analysis milestone. Solver settings (large-deflection on, sparse direct solver, Newton-Raphson convergence 0.5% force residual) were locked prior to any comparison with experimental data. No post-hoc tuning of solver parameters was performed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical code verification",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Benchmark problems with known analytical solutions exercised; element formulations verified against published NAFEMS benchmarks.",
      "rationale": "Three NAFEMS benchmark cases relevant to the contact and bending physics of the pedicle screw model were executed: (1) Hertzian contact between a cylinder and flat plate, (2) cantilever beam with large-deflection loading, and (3) threaded-joint pull-out in a simplified axisymmetric geometry. Predicted displacements and peak stresses agreed with reference solutions within 1.2%, 0.8%, and 2.1% respectively, all within the 5% acceptance band. Element formulations (SOLID186, CONTA174, TARGE170) are consistent with those used in the pedicle screw assembly model."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Discretization error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Mesh convergence study performed on QoIs; Richardson extrapolation or GCI reported; discretization error bounded below 5% of QoI.",
      "rationale": "A three-level mesh refinement study was conducted on the screw shank and screw-rod interface regions, which govern stiffness and yield force predictions. Global element size was halved between each level (coarse: 0.8 mm, medium: 0.4 mm, fine: 0.2 mm). Richardson extrapolation yielded GCI values of 1.8% (stiffness), 2.4% (yield force), and 3.1% (force at 40 mm), all below the 5% threshold. The medium mesh was selected for production runs as the fine mesh offered negligible additional accuracy at substantially higher computational cost."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Numerical solver error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Convergence of nonlinear iterations confirmed; residual norms reported; time-step or load-step sensitivity checked.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear force residual norms converged to below 0.5% at each load step. Load-step sensitivity was assessed by halving the applied displacement increment from 0.5 mm to 0.25 mm; QoI differences were less than 0.3%. Sparse direct solver was used, eliminating iterative solver round-off as a concern. All runs achieved full convergence with no bisection events beyond the first five load steps."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Use error",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 2,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Analysis performed by qualified analyst; independent peer review of boundary conditions, material assignments, and contact definitions completed.",
      "rationale": "The primary analyst holds a PhD in mechanical engineering with eight years of FEA experience in orthopaedic implant modeling. Boundary conditions (fixed base block, prescribed displacement at superior block), material assignments (Ti-6Al-4V screw: E=114 GPa, UHMWPE block: E=0.9 GPa), and contact pair definitions were independently reviewed by a second senior analyst not involved in model construction. All discrepancies identified in review (two minor contact pair orientation issues) were corrected before any comparison with experimental data was performed."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Governing physics (contact, large deformation, material nonlinearity) captured; simplifying assumptions documented and justified; sensitivity of QoIs to model-form choices assessed.",
      "rationale": "The model captures frictional contact (μ=0.2, augmented Lagrange), geometric nonlinearity (large-deflection formulation), and bilinear isotropic hardening for Ti-6Al-4V (tangent modulus 1.14 GPa). Simplifying assumptions — omission of screw thread helix geometry (replaced by equivalent bonded contact at thread engagement length), rigid rod assumption — were each subjected to sensitivity analysis. Thread helix omission introduced less than 1.5% difference in stiffness relative to a full-thread pilot model. Rod rigidity assumption was validated against a deformable rod sub-model showing 0.4% QoI difference. Both simplifications are accepted as inconsequential for the compression-bending COU."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties sourced from traceable literature or direct measurement; geometric dimensions from calibrated CMM; input uncertainty characterised.",
      "rationale": "Ti-6Al-4V elastic modulus and yield strength were drawn from ASM Handbook Vol. 2 and confirmed against three peer-reviewed literature sources; coefficient of variation across sources was 1.8%. UHMWPE block properties were measured in-house via uniaxial compression testing (n=5 specimens, CV 4.2%). Screw geometry was digitised using a Zeiss Contura CMM (uncertainty ±2 µm). Input uncertainty was propagated through a 200-sample Latin hypercube study; the resulting 95th-percentile QoI variation was 3.4%, well within acceptance bounds."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Sufficient sample size to characterise experimental variability; specimens representative of production geometry; traceability of specimens documented.",
      "rationale": "Eleven non-cannulated 7.5 mm pedicle screw constructs were tested across two independent laboratories (FDA OSEL, n=6; DePuy Synthes, n=5). All specimens were drawn from the same production lot (lot 2019-NC-75-A), with dimensional inspection confirming conformance to drawing within ±0.05 mm on critical features. Experimental coefficient of variation for stiffness was 4.8%, for yield force 6.2%, and for force at 40 mm 5.9%, consistent with published F1717 inter-laboratory variability. Sample size provides adequate statistical power to detect a 10% QoI difference at 80% power (power analysis: n=9 required)."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios or multiple load configurations are evaluated; environmental conditions (temperature, humidity, lubricant) are controlled and documented.",
      "rationale": "All validation experiments were conducted under a single test configuration: quasi-static compression-bending at 5° offset per ASTM F1717, displacement rate 5 mm/min, ambient laboratory conditions (22±2°C, 45±10% RH), dry (no simulated body fluid). This configuration represents the standard regulatory submission condition and is the configuration most directly relevant to the COU. The team acknowledges that the ASME V&V 40 framework calls for evaluation across a range of conditions to achieve Level 3 for this factor; however, the single-condition approach is consistent with FDA guidance for Class II pedicle screw submissions and with prior FDA-accepted submissions for analogous constructs. Expert judgment from the clinical biomechanics team, supported by a review of 14 published F1717 datasets, indicates that the dry quasi-static condition is the most discriminating for construct stiffness and yield force and that wet or dynamic conditions do not systematically alter the rank ordering of construct performance. Furthermore, the conservative nature of the 10% acceptance bound provides margin against condition-dependent variability. On this basis, the assessment team concluded that the evidence base, while not meeting the formal breadth criterion for Level 3, provides sufficient confidence for the Medium risk COU, and the overall package was advanced for acceptance."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Model inputs matched to experimental conditions; any differences between experimental and modelled parameters quantified and their effect on QoIs assessed.",
      "rationale": "All model boundary conditions were set to match the experimental test fixture geometry as measured by CMM (offset angle 5.0°±0.1°, grip separation 100.0±0.2 mm). Material properties used in the model were drawn from the same production lot as the test specimens where possible. Frictional coefficient at the block-screw interface was estimated from a dedicated friction measurement sub-study (n=3 block pairs, μ=0.20±0.03). Sensitivity of QoIs to ±15% variation in friction coefficient was less than 2.1%, confirming that this parameter does not drive prediction uncertainty. Displacement rate effects (quasi-static assumption) were verified by comparing 1 mm/min and 10 mm/min experimental results, which differed by less than 1.0% in all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric (E/uval) computed; pre-specified acceptance criterion applied; comparison covers all primary QoIs.",
      "rationale": "E/uval was computed for all three primary QoIs following the ASME V&V 40 Eq. 5-1 formulation, incorporating both model prediction uncertainty (from LHS propagation) and experimental measurement uncertainty (from inter-laboratory variability). Results: stiffness E/uval=0.87, yield force E/uval=1.31, force at 40 mm E/uval=1.62. All three values are below the pre-specified threshold of 1.96. Percent differences are 4.2%, 6.1%, and 7.8% respectively, all below the 10% bound. Acceptance criteria were locked in the validation plan prior to any experimental data unblinding."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs are directly linked to the clinical or regulatory question; QoI selection justified in the context of failure modes and COU.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 as the primary mechanical performance descriptors for pedicle screw constructs. These QoIs are directly linked to the clinical failure modes of interest: loss of fixation (stiffness degradation) and implant fracture (yield force). The 40 mm displacement endpoint captures post-yield energy absorption relevant to fatigue fracture risk assessment. All three QoIs are reported in the FDA guidance for Class II pedicle screw 510(k) submissions and are the quantities examined in comparative device performance claims."
    },
    {
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario geometry, loading, and boundary conditions match or bound the COU; any gaps between validation scenario and COU are documented and their impact assessed.",
      "rationale": "The validation activity directly replicates the COU: the same screw design (non-cannulated 7.5 mm), the same test standard (ASTM F1717), the same QoIs, and the same acceptance bounds used in the regulatory submission. The FEA model used in validation is identical to the model used for the COU prediction (same mesh, same material cards, same solver settings). No extrapolation beyond the validated geometry or loading envelope is required for the COU. The only gap is the single-condition limitation noted under Test Conditions, which has been addressed in that factor's assessment. The validation activities are therefore judged highly relevant to the COU."
    }
  ],
  "hasWeakener": [],
  "hasDecisionRecord": {
    "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/decision/nagaraja-cou1-dr-001",
    "type": "DecisionRecord",
    "actor": "https://uofa.net/synth/actor/nagaraja-credibility-team",
    "role": "Credibility assessment team",
    "outcome": "Accepted",
    "rationale": "The credibility assessment team reviewed all 13 ASME V&V 40 factors for COU1. Twelve of thirteen factors achieved their required credibility level. The single shortfall — Test conditions achieving Level 2 against a required Level 3 — was deliberated at length. The team noted that: (1) the single-condition F1717 protocol is the FDA-standard benchmark for Class II pedicle screw submissions and has been accepted in multiple prior 510(k) clearances; (2) a review of 14 published F1717 datasets showed that dry quasi-static compression-bending is the most mechanically discriminating condition and that wet or cyclic conditions do not alter the direction or magnitude of inter-construct differences in a way that would affect the regulatory conclusion; (3) the quantitative acceptance criteria (E/uval < 1.96, percent difference < 10%) were met with margin on all three QoIs, providing a buffer against any condition-dependent variability not captured by the single test configuration; and (4) the model risk level (3) and decision consequence (Medium) are consistent with the Medium assurance level, for which the overall evidence package — eleven specimens across two independent laboratories, fully traceable inputs, mesh-convergence-verified discretization, and pre-specified acceptance criteria — is judged commensurate. The team concluded that the weight of evidence supports model acceptance for the stated COU and that the Test conditions shortfall does not materially undermine confidence in the validation conclusion given the conservatism embedded in the acceptance bounds and the regulatory precedent for this test configuration.",
    "decidedAt": "2026-04-19T00:00:00Z"
  },
